<h2>Installation completed</h2>

<p>Congratulation! The LiveChat Starter Kit is installed.</p>

<h4>Operator Console</h4>

<p>If you are installing this via nuget, you will have to download the operator console (Windows Forms) application to answer and chat with your visitor.</p>

<p>You can download it here: <a href=" http://livechatstarterkit.codeplex.com/releases"> http://livechatstarterkit.codeplex.com/releases</a></p>

<p>You might want to start the Operator Console and click on "Configure" to set the correct Url for the webservice communication.</p>

<p>It could look similar to this: http://@Request.Url.Host/LCSKServices/OpServices.asmx</p>

<p>Sign in with the user 'admin' and the password you supply on the last page.</p>

<h4>Adding chat button to your pages</h4>

Here is the code to add to your pages where you want the button to appears.


<blockquote>
<p>
@("<a href=\"/livechat/session\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"/livechat/chatimage?r=@Url.Encode(Request.UrlReferrer != null ? Request.UrlReferrer.ToString() : \"\")\" alt=\"Chat button\" /></a>")
</p>
</blockquote>

<p><strong>You might want to change the online and offline image located on /content/LCSK/online.jpg and offline.jpg</strong></p>

<h5>Have a nice day!</h5>

